{
  "doc_id": "44927",
  "text": "The cooperative effect between human recombinant IFN-g (hrIFN-g) and nerve growth factor (NGF) for induction of HUCBNP neuronal differentiation. HUCBNP were treated for either 7 (white bars) or 14 (black bars) days with 1 ng/ml hrIFN-g, 10 ng/ml NGF or a combination of both or left untreated. The differentiation expressed by neurites elongation (E) was measured as described in Materials and methods. * vs untreated Po0.01; ** vs treatment with individual factor Po0.01. HUCBNP, HUCB-derived neuronal progenitors. [CITATION_1] and activation of ERK1/2 pathway, 27 a major essential pathway for induction of neurite outgrowths. [CITATION_2] Other immunologically derived cytokines, such as interleukin-1 and interleukin-6 have also been shown to induce neurite outgrowths in neurons in vitro [CITATION_3] and in vivo. [CITATION_4] Furthermore, HUCB-derived progenitors secrete large amounts of these interleukins as well as angiogenic and neurotrophic factors, [CITATION_5] which in an autocrine manner may be responsible for the neurite outgrowths and maintenance of the differentiated phenotype.",
